The '''[[Brigham Young University]] Museum of Paleontology''' was started in 1976 around the collection of [[James A. Jensen]]. For many years, it was known as the ''BYU Earth Science Museum'',<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/156955/Y-RESEARCHERS-START-TO-PIECE-PUZZLE-OF-DINOSAUR-BONES.html |title= Y. Researchers Start to Piece Puzzle of Dinosaur Bones |first= Brooke |last= Adams |date= April 12, 1991 |newspaper= [[Deseret News]] }}</ref> and most of the collection was in storage under the [[LaVell Edwards Stadium]].<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/595096047/Fact-or-fiction.html |title= Fact or fiction: Are dinosaur bones stored underneath BYU's LaVell Edwards Stadium? |date= October 7, 2004 |newspaper= Deseret News }}</ref>
In October 2009, the museum held a grand opening of its new facilities during BYU homecoming week. With the {{convert|5000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} addition, it now displays most of the collection. The change of name clarifies that the museum actually houses a large collection of [[dinosaur]] bones and other [[fossils]].<ref name="Deseret News 2009-10-22">{{citation |url= http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705338766/Y-science-museum-expanded-renamed.html |title= Y. science museum expanded, renamed |newspaper= Deseret News |date= October 22, 2009 |first= Sara |last= Israelsen-Hartley }}</ref>
The museum is currently directed by [[Rodney Scheetz]], who was one of Jensen's students at BYU. Its main purpose is to facilitate research, but it is open to the public.
